@flexiarg peeragogy/wrapper
@title Have Someone Whose Job Is to Stitch the Pieces Together
@keywords integrative-function, summarising, status, weekly-roundup, role, benkler
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project conveners
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/heartbeat peeragogy/roles peeragogy/roadmap]

! conclusion: Commons-based peer production needs both the ability to contribute small pieces and an integrative function that stitches those pieces together.  The wrapper is whoever or whatever performs that stitching — through periodic summaries, status framings, or maintained overviews — so contributors and newcomers can see what the project currently is.  Without a wrapper, small contributions accumulate without composing into a legible whole.
  + context: Distributed peer-learning projects produce more fragments than any individual contributor can hold in mind: messages, edits, drafts, threads, side-projects.  Newcomers cannot orient.  Long-tenured members lose track of what others are doing.  The wrapper's labour is not new content but legibility: a periodic act of saying "here is what the project is right now" that lets the rest of the work remain small.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: contribution granularity ↔ project legibility.
    Real: small contributions are easy to make and easy to lose track of.  The smaller the contribution unit, the more the project depends on someone explicitly composing the units into a story.  Without that composition, the small contributions look like noise; with it, they become a project.
    Irreducible: no individual contributor can both make a contribution and simultaneously hold the whole project in their head.  The wrapping work is structurally separate from the contributing work.
    Active: the pull recurs at every cadence boundary (week, sprint, release) and whenever a newcomer arrives needing orientation.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Periodic roundup: a named person publishes a recurring summary (weekly digest, monthly report) that names what happened, who did what, and what is open.  The roundup is itself the wrapper artefact.
    (2) Tended overview: a shared page (project main page, dashboard, README) that someone keeps current.  Wrapping is continuous rather than periodic.
    (3) Briefing on demand: the wrapper writes orientation pieces when someone arrives or returns, rather than on a schedule.  Lower routine cost; risks newcomers arriving when no wrapper is on duty.
    (4) Multi-wrapper rotation: the role rotates among several people, each wrapping a different facet (technical state, social state, external relations).  Spreads cost; needs explicit handoff between rotations.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: a newcomer can read a single recent artefact and form an accurate picture of where the project is.  Failing when: orientation requires reading the full message history or asking individual contributors what is going on.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Stale main page: the canonical overview describes a project state from months ago.
    - Repeated orientation requests: the same "what is the status of X?" question recurs because no answer is captured.
    - Fragmented memory: each contributor knows their own piece and no one knows the whole.
    - Recognition starvation: contributors stop knowing whether their work landed because nothing names it.
